### T3 — GW-03: Sloped wall geometry

  You are implementing GW-03 in a BIM web app (monorepo at /Users/jhoetter/repos/bim-ai).
  Start by pulling main: git checkout main && git pull origin main

  Goal

  Modify makeWallMesh in packages/web/src/Viewport.tsx to build a trapezoidal/triangular
  prism when the wall has roofAttachmentId pointing at a roof element. The default behaviour
  (BoxGeometry) must be unchanged for walls without that field.

  Prerequisites (already in main after Batch 1 merges)

  - roofAttachmentId coercion exists in store.ts
  - roofHeightAtPoint exported from packages/web/src/viewport/roofHeightSampler.ts

  Step 1 — import roofHeightAtPoint

  At the top of packages/web/src/Viewport.tsx, add:
    import { roofHeightAtPoint } from './viewport/roofHeightSampler';

  Step 2 — modify the makeWallMesh signature

  makeWallMesh currently (line ~773):
    function makeWallMesh(wall: WallElem, elevM: number, paint: ViewportPaintBundle | null): THREE.Mesh

  Change it to also accept elementsById:
    function makeWallMesh(
      wall: WallElem,
      elevM: number,
      paint: ViewportPaintBundle | null,
      elementsById?: Record<string, Element>,
    ): THREE.Mesh | THREE.Group

  (The return type widens to Group only for the sloped variant; if you'd rather keep it Mesh,
  build the sloped geometry still as a Mesh with a custom BufferGeometry.)

  Step 3 — sloped geometry branch

  Add this logic at the beginning of makeWallMesh, BEFORE the BoxGeometry code:

  if (wall.roofAttachmentId && elementsById) {
    const roof = elementsById[wall.roofAttachmentId];
    if (roof?.kind === 'roof') {
      return makeSlopedWallMesh(wall, roof, elevM, paint, elementsById);
    }
  }

  Step 4 — implement makeSlopedWallMesh

  Add a new helper function above makeWallMesh:

  function makeSlopedWallMesh(
    wall: WallElem,
    roof: Extract<Element, { kind: 'roof' }>,
    elevM: number,
    paint: ViewportPaintBundle | null,
    elementsById: Record<string, Element>,
  ): THREE.Mesh {
    // Wall corners in plan space (mm)
    const sx = wall.start.xMm;  const sz = wall.start.yMm;
    const ex = wall.end.xMm;    const ez = wall.end.yMm;

    const dx = ex - sx;  const dz = ez - sz;
    const len = Math.max(1, Math.hypot(dx, dz));
    const ux = dx / len;  const uz = dz / len;  // unit along wall
    const nx = -uz;       const nz =  ux;        // unit normal (rightward when facing wall direction)

    const thick = THREE.MathUtils.clamp(wall.thicknessMm / 1000, 0.05, 2);
    const halfT = thick / 2;

    // Four base corners in plan (mm), extruded ±halfT along normal
    // (We compute roof height at wall centreline midpoints for each end)
    const hStart = roofHeightAtPoint(roof, elementsById, sx, sz);  // metres
    const hEnd   = roofHeightAtPoint(roof, elementsById, ex, ez);  // metres

    // Base elevation
    const yBase = elevM;

    // 8 vertices of a trapezoidal prism (front face, back face)
    // Front face: +halfT along normal  |  Back face: -halfT along normal
    const sxF = (sx / 1000) + nx * halfT;  const szF = (sz / 1000) + nz * halfT;
    const exF = (ex / 1000) + nx * halfT;  const ezF = (ez / 1000) + nz * halfT;
    const sxB = (sx / 1000) - nx * halfT;  const szB = (sz / 1000) - nz * halfT;
    const exB = (ex / 1000) - nx * halfT;  const ezB = (ez / 1000) - nz * halfT;

    // positions: 24 vertices (6 quads × 4 = 24, but we triangulate → 6 quads × 2 tris × 3 verts = 36)
    // Easier: build with indexed geometry. 8 unique verts, 12 triangles.
    const positions = new Float32Array([
      sxF, yBase,   szF,  // 0 start-front-base
      exF, yBase,   ezF,  // 1 end-front-base
      exF, hEnd,    ezF,  // 2 end-front-top
      sxF, hStart,  szF,  // 3 start-front-top
      sxB, yBase,   szB,  // 4 start-back-base
      exB, yBase,   ezB,  // 5 end-back-base
      exB, hEnd,    ezB,  // 6 end-back-top
      sxB, hStart,  szB,  // 7 start-back-top
    ]);

    const indices = new Uint16Array([
      0,1,2, 0,2,3,   // front face
      5,4,7, 5,7,6,   // back face
      4,0,3, 4,3,7,   // left cap (start)
      1,5,6, 1,6,2,   // right cap (end)
      4,5,1, 4,1,0,   // bottom
      3,2,6, 3,6,7,   // top (sloped)
    ]);

    const geom = new THREE.BufferGeometry();
    geom.setAttribute('position', new THREE.BufferAttribute(positions, 3));
    geom.setIndex(new THREE.BufferAttribute(indices, 1));
    geom.computeVertexNormals();

    const mat = new THREE.MeshStandardMaterial({
      color: categoryColorOr(paint, 'wall'),
      roughness: paint?.categories.wall.roughness ?? 0.85,
      metalness: paint?.categories.wall.metalness ?? 0.0,
    });
    const mesh = new THREE.Mesh(geom, mat);
    mesh.userData.bimPickId = wall.id;
    addEdges(mesh);
    return mesh;
  }

  Step 5 — update the call sites of makeWallMesh

  In the wall dispatch block (around line 1979–2022) there are TWO calls to makeWallMesh:
  1. The placeholder at the end: obj = makeWallMesh(e, elev, paint);
  2. Also check if there's a non-CSG path.

  Pass curr (the elementsById) as the 4th argument at both call sites:
    obj = makeWallMesh(e, elev, paint, curr);

  Also check if the CSG path uses height from e.heightMm — if a sloped wall has
  roofAttachmentId, skip CSG dispatch for it (CSG worker only knows BoxGeometry):
  After the if (CSG_ENABLED && (doors.length > 0 || wins.length > 0)) check, add a guard:
    if (CSG_ENABLED && (doors.length > 0 || wins.length > 0) && !e.roofAttachmentId) {

  Verification

    pnpm --filter @bim-ai/web typecheck
    pnpm --filter @bim-ai/web test -- --run

  Both must pass. Then manually test in the dev server:
  1. Create a wall and a gable roof at the same level.
  2. Set roofAttachmentId on the wall (via browser console or by temporarily adding a test
  button in the UI) to the roof's id.
  3. Verify the wall top follows the roof slope in the 3D view.

  Branch & commit

  Branch: gw-03-sloped-wall-geometry
  Commit message: "feat(viewport): sloped wall geometry follows roof via roofAttachmentId"
  Push to origin.

